  "prompt": "Why is a quadratic equation called 'quadratic', though it has a degree of two and quad means four (eg : x^2-2x-3)?",
  "response": "The term \"quadratic\" comes from the Latin word \"quadratus,\" which means \"square.\" In mathematics, it refers to an equation involving a squared term (x\u00b2) as the highest degree term.\n\nThe word \"quad\" might make you think of four, but in this context, it relates to the square (x\u00b2) of a variable. So a quadratic equation is essentially an equation where the highest power of the variable is 2, or squared.\n\nThe standard form of a quadratic equation is ax\u00b2 + bx + c = 0, where:\n- a \u2260 0\n- a, b, and c are constants\n- x is the variable\n\nExamples:\n- x\u00b2 - 2x - 3 = 0\n- 2x\u00b2 + 5x + 3 = 0\n\nThe \"quad\" in quadratic refers to the squared term (x\u00b2), not the number four. This can be a bit confusing because \"quad\" often means four in other contexts, but in mathematics, it specifically relates to squaring.",
